body: @kit1980 This looks like exactly the same issue you just hit (and I believe have a fix for?).

@mrry I think my issue is different, but probably related.
I'll take a look.

I used git bisect to find the first instance of the bug and narrowed it down to the following commit.
```
commit 25e261f1961b968acb1d6e25f18699729707ccc1
Author: Derek Murray <Derek.Murray@microsoft.com>
Date:   Tue Apr 6 16:49:34 2021 -0700

    Avoid passing zero bias to Gemm in gradients (#7244)

    * Avoid passing zero bias to Gemm in gradients

    The bias argument to Gemm is optional and defaults to zero. Therefore we do not need to generate zero initializers and pass them to that argument.

    * Remove unused declaration.

 .../orttraining/core/graph/gradient_builder.cc     | 38 +++++++---------------
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+), 26 deletions(-)
```

I think I may have inadvertently stumbled on the possible cause of this issue.

Gemm defines the 3rd input C as optional.

While doing some testing of a Gemm implementation I removed the C input.

The error I got was: `This is an invalid model. Error in Node:node1 : Node (node1) has input size 2 not in range [min=3, max=3].`

It looks like the graph generation for Gemm may not be properly handling the optional input C.
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Gemm

I don't know if the graph generation would also affect the gradient op as well but I suspect it is possible.

Since I am not completely sure this issue is directly related to this issue I will make a new issue.

@georgen117
OK, I think I figured this out.
The issue is that the model from https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4553416/mnist.zip has ONNX opset 10.
For Gemm, the 3rd input is optional only since opset 11.
PR https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7244 assumes "The bias argument to Gemm is optional and defaults to zero", so it implicitly assumes that opset is greater or equal than 11.

One way to resolve this is to load ONNX models from https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4553416/mnist.zip via ONNX Python API and re-save with a newer opset.

@kit1980
> Have you created the new issue?

Not yet. I plan on doing it today.  I wanted to take the time to make clear reproduction steps

> What was the ONNX opset version for the model? For older opsets the 3rd Gemm input was mandatory.

The issue with Gemm was reproduced using the unit tests.  I assumed the unit tests are the latest opset version. (Please correct me if I am wrong) I just commented out the one of the C inputs in the unit test and that reproduced the issue.

>One way to resolve this is to load ONNX models from https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/4553416/mnist.zip via ONNX Python API and re-save with a newer opset.

I will give this a try.  It would be really great to be able to use the mnist training sample again it was really valuable as we added backward ops to our execution provider.

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
If you run Gemm without providing the optional C input it will fail to run saying `This is an invalid model`

Add this test to the gemm_test.cc unit test code
```
template <typename T>
void TestGemmNoTransNoCInput() {
  auto run_test = [](bool b_is_initializer) {
    OpTester test("Gemm");

    test.AddAttribute("transA", (int64_t)0);
    test.AddAttribute("transB", (int64_t)0);
    test.AddAttribute("alpha", 1.0f);
    test.AddAttribute("beta", 1.0f);

    test.AddInput<T>("A", {2, 4},
                     {1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f, 4.0f,
                      -1.0f, -2.0f, -3.0f, -4.0f});
    test.AddInput<T>("B", {4, 3}, std::vector<T>(12, 1.0f), b_is_initializer);
    test.AddOutput<T>("Y", {2, 3},
                      {10.0f, 10.0f, 10.0f,
                       -10.0f, -10.0f, -10.0f});
    test.Run();
  };

  run_test(false);
  // NNAPI EP requires weight to be an initializer
  run_test(true);
}

TEST(GemmOpTest, GemmNoTransNoCInput_float) {
  TestGemmNoTransNoCInput<float>();
}

TEST(GemmOpTest, GemmNoTransNoCInput_double) {
  TestGemmNoTransNoCInput<double>();
}
```

This is a modification of an already existing test I simply removed the C input.

According to the ONNX specification the 3rd input is optional
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Gemm

So the Gemm operator should still run.

**Urgency**
To the best of my knowledge this is not blocking anyone.
The issue seen here may be related to another issue reported by me: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7506


**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): built from source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.1 (close to the tip of master)
- Python version: Python 3.8.3
- Visual Studio version (if applicable):  Visual Sudio Pro 2019 Version 4.8.04084
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): N/A (not yet tried issue on linux)
- CUDA/cuDNN version: N/A using CPU build
- GPU model and memory: from unit test see code above

**To Reproduce**
- Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.

Copy pase unit test code given above into `onnxruntime\test\providers\cpu\math\gemm_test.cc`
build the code: `.\build.bat --config RelWithDebInfo --parallel  --build_shared_lib --cmake_generator "Visual Studio 16 2019"`
run the unit tests in quesiton
`.\build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\RelWithDebInfo\onnxruntime_test_all.exe --test_filter=GemmOpTest.GemmNoTransNoCInput*`

**Expected behavior**
The two tests should run and pass without failure.

body:
I replied to https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/8737
The default opset for OpTester is 7, so the same cause.
I'm closing this for now, feel free to re-open if needed.
